Ken Stanley and I are happy to announce our =
new article, &quot;Investigating Biological Assumptions through Radical Reimplem=
entation,&quot; which has been accepted to be published in Artificial Life journ=
al. It&#39;s available for download at: 



http://eplex.cs.ucf.edu/publicatio=
ns/2014/lehman-alife14a



This largely philosophical position article may=
 be of interest to readers of this list because it argues in defense of eng=
ineering approaches to artificial life research (like NEAT and HyperNEAT) t=
hat are biologically implausible by design. The idea is to provide a thorou=
gh philosophical response to the common critique that some of us often enco=
unter, i.e. that engineering-style approaches like novelty search or HyperN=
EAT may be interesting and practical, but have little relevance to understa=
nd biology. 



The central problem the article addresses is the difficult=
y in inferring general principles of evolution and intelligence from the si=
ngle example of life on Earth. For example, from only observing animal inte=
lligence on Earth, it is hard to separate with confidence the core principl=
es of intelligence from aspects that are only coincidental (i.e. what detai=
ls of the natural world are only &quot;implementation details&quot;?).



The sugges=
ted approach, called &quot;radical reimplementation,&quot; requires first formulating=
 an abstract hypothesis about the crux of a biologically-relevant phenomeno=
n. For example, one hypothesis about development in nature is that it may p=
rimarily serve to instantiate a phenotype as a function of geometry (the mo=
tivation for HyperNEAT). The main idea is then to return from the abstract =
hypothesis to a concrete implementation, but to have this implementation di=
verge as radically as possible from existing biological example (e.g. CPPNs=
 as a radical reimplementation of development). Similarly to how creating a=
n airplane divergent from flying animals demonstrates our understanding of =
flight, if the radical reimplementation exhibits similar output to biology,=
 evidence is provided for the underlying abstract hypothesis. The benefit i=
s that radical reimplementation better isolates the hypothesis to be tested=
 from all of the confounding features found in approaches more directly ins=
pired by nature (e.g. seeing an airplane better illuminates the general pri=
nciples of flight than does an artificial bird). 



The paper explains ra=
dical reimplementation in detail, and describes several examples of researc=
h that could be interpreted through its lens: the subsumption architecture,=
 Avida, HyperNEAT, and novelty search. While there are many valid approache=
s to alife research, the hope is that the article provides a rationale for =
why divergence from nature can be just as principled as the minimization of=
 deviations from biology (and attempts to justify such deviations) typical =
of much alife research. 



We hope you enjoy the paper and look forward t=
o any philosophical discussion about alife research it helps to foster.  

