 largely philosophical position article may be of interest to readers of th=
is list because it argues in defense of engineering approaches to artificia=
l life research (like NEAT and HyperNEAT) that are biologically implausible=
 by design. The idea is to provide a thorough philosophical response to the=
 common critique that some of us often encounter, i.e. that engineering-sty=
le approaches like novelty search or HyperNEAT may be interesting and pract=
ical, but have little relevance to understand biology.&nbsp;&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;=
&lt;p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The central problem the article addresses is the=
 difficulty in inferring general principles of evolution and intelligence f=
rom the single example of life on Earth. For example, from only observing a=
nimal intelligence on Earth, it is hard to separate with confidence the cor=
e principles of intelligence from aspects that are only coincidental (i.e. =
what details of the natural world are only &quot;implementation details&quo=
t;?).&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The suggested approach, call=
ed &quot;radical reimplementation,&quot; requires first formulating an abst=
ract hypothesis about the crux of a biologically-relevant phenomenon. For e=
xample, one hypothesis about development in nature is that it may primarily=
 serve to instantiate a phenotype as a function of geometry (the motivation=
 for HyperNEAT). The main idea is then to return from the abstract hypothes=
is to a concrete implementation, but to have this implementation diverge as=
 radically as possible from existing biological example (e.g. CPPNs as a ra=
dical reimplementation of development). Similarly to how creating an airpla=
ne divergent from flying animals demonstrates our understanding of flight, =
if the radical reimplementation exhibits similar output to biology, evidenc=
e is provided for the underlying abstract hypothesis. The benefit is that r=
adical reimplementation better isolates the hypothesis to be tested from al=
l of the confounding features found in approaches more directly inspired by=
 nature (e.g. seeing an airplane better illuminates the general principles =
of flight than does an artificial bird).&nbsp;&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;o:p&gt;=
&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The paper explains radical reimplementation in detail, and des=
cribes several examples of research that could be interpreted through its l=
ens: the subsumption architecture, Avida, HyperNEAT, and novelty search. Wh=
ile there are many valid approaches to alife research, the hope is that the=
 article provides a rationale for why divergence from nature can be just as=
 principled as the minimization of deviations from biology (and attempts to=
 justify such deviations) typical of much alife research.&nbsp;&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;=
/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;o:p&gt;&lt;/o:p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;We hope you enjoy the paper and look forward =
